default&#xa0;default1.0default              defaultIsdefault cycling safe, particularly in towns and citiesdefault?default&#xa0;
default1.1default              
defaultThe first point to make is that ‘safety’ is always relative – there is no absolutely safe mode of 
defaulttransport.  Cycling in the UK, expressed in terms of casualties per mile cycled, is safer than other countries such as the US, but less
default safe 
defaultthan 
defaultcountries such as 
defaultthe Netherlands and Denmark.
default  The aim must be to ma
defaultke cycling 
defaultin the UK 
defaultas safe as in the 
defaultbest
default countries.
default  However, it should be recognised that the risk of a cycling fatality in the UK, per mile travelled, is about half what it was 20 years ago
default. M
defaultany people believe cycling to be more hazardous than walking, yet deaths per mile travelled by cyc
defaultlist have been lower that for pedestrians for every year since 1994
default.  
default&#xa0;
default1.2default              
defaultUnfortunately 
defaultthe risk per mile of being killed or seriously injured in when cycling has increased
default more recently
default, and this is worrying, particularly since the risks for other mode
defaults of travel have continued to decline.  The reasons for this are not fully clear, but many of the fatalities that have occurred have involved cyclists and HGVs
default, particularly when the HGV is turning left at a junction.
default 
default&#xa0;
default1.3default              
defaultThe health benefits of cycling a
defaultlso need to be taken into account – people die from illnesses brought on by inactivity as well as through road traffic accidents.  Cycling has been 
defaultshown to significantly reduce the risk of heart disease, diabetes and cancers, which together kill over a hu
defaultndred times the number of people who die 
defaulton the roads.
default&#xa0;
default1.4default              
defaultUrban areas are complex and present a characteristic combination of hazards that 
defaultresult in, per
default 
defaultmile cycled
default, 
defaulta higher number of collisions involving a cyclist than in 
defaultrural areas.  Cyclists are 
defaultmore likely to encounter congestion and compete with motorists
default, particularly at junctions where most collisions take place.  Due to the higher traffic speeds involved though, collisions in rural ar
defaulteas tend to be more severe – when they do occur the cyclist
default has a greater chance of being killed or seriously injured.
default 
